Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
After President Trump fired her for cause (alleged mortgage fraud), former Fed Governor Cook is expected to sue.

This massive administrative state/separation of powers case will likely go to the Supreme Court.

Let's break down why President Trump is expected to win. üßµ https://t.co/MhkQ7QtY7P

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: As the Supreme Court clarified a few months ago: the default rule is that Article II of the Constitution grants the President the authority to remove any federal official wielding executive power for any reason the President deems appropriate, including policy disagreements. https://t.co/g68DASyUOM

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Decades ago, a series of Supreme Court cases established a few narrow exceptions to the default rule.

In recent years, however, SCOTUS reaffirmed the default rule and the President's authority by significantly narrowing those already limited exceptions.
https://t.co/euQyZgljpa

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
For example, in the recent Trump v. Wilcox case, SCOTUS upheld President Trump's firing of several unelected bureaucrats who were obstructing his agenda.

However, the Court also suggested there may be limitations to this power for "quasi-private" bodies like the Fed. https://t.co/KjTIbfuu2v

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
So SCOTUS has suggested‚Äîbut not definitively concluded‚Äîthat Fed Board Governors can be removed only "for cause."

That means the safest route to fire a Fed governor is for the President to state a sufficient reason‚Äîa "cause"‚Äîto fire him or her.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
In Cook's termination letter, President Trump explained his cause for firing her: She likely committed mortgage fraud and is now under federal criminal investigation.

The Fed Board‚Äîwhich indirectly sets mortgage interest rates‚Äîcan't have a member who committed mortgage fraud. https://t.co/RHWI8UONYL

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
By explaining his cause for firing her, President Trump has carefully followed the law and acted within the bounds of SCOTUS precedent.
https://t.co/1piE7HJAo9

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
When Cook sues, the key issue will be whether a court can review President Trump's motive for firing her.

In other words, will courts try to second-guess the President's decision (like in NY v. Dept of Comm., in yellow below) and claim this cause is pretextual or insufficient? https://t.co/CldKJUEL1F

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
The Supreme Court has expressly agreed with this reasoning.

From its 1901 Reagan decision: "removal for cause, when causes are not defined nor removal for cause provided for, is a matter of discretion, and not reviewable."
https://t.co/4bXIFaeYWX

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
I read the Supreme Court reasoning in Trump v. US to mean a court cannot review the President's motive for firing a federal official.

That means courts can‚Äôt second-guess whether President Trump's stated motive is the actual motive.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Given that (1) strong evidence supports his stated reason for this firing and (2) his reasoning is not reviewable by a court, President Trump has the law on his side here.

President Trump should win this important administrative state and separation of powers case.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
ICYMI: Texas border cities like Laredo continue to rank among the safest in the nation. According to @FBI data, rates of murder and violent crime remain lower than in many major cities across the country. In Laredo, the murder rate is 2 per 100,000 people, less than half the national rate of 5 per 100,000. In Rio Grande City, there were no murders at all last year.

This data reflects the dedication of local leaders and residents to building neighborhoods where people can live, work, and thrive without fear. When neighbors feel confident engaging in community life, it strengthens connections and fosters a sense of belonging that unites us all. Peace and stability create opportunity, hope, and a brighter future for everyone living here.

I'll continue to support the committed men and women in law enforcement who work tirelessly to keep South Texas protected. Backing our law enforcement is supporting safer streets, stronger families, and the future of our communities.

Name: Massie, Thomas
text:
Last night, I had dinner with and spoke to more than 100 constituents at a Lewis County Chamber of Commerce event.

As a native of Lewis County, and the former County Judge/Executive, it was a pleasure to see so many familiar faces, including current Judge/Executive George Sparks, Lewis County Attorney Ben Harrison, Kentucky State Representative Patrick Flannery, Kentucky Secretary of State Michael Adams, and Warrior Ridge founder Landon Bentley. Thanks to Lewis County Sheriff Johnny Bivens and his deputies for keeping Lewis County safe. I shared a few stories from my time in local office and expressed my sincere appreciation for the work our county officials do.

I also expressed how seriously I take my vote in Congress. My vote does not belong to the Republican Party, to the Speaker of the House, or to whomever is in the White House‚Äîit belongs to the 750,000 people of the Fourth District. One issue that often influences how I vote is our rising national debt. I showed those in attendance the debt badge I built and wear and explained how it is meant to raise awareness among my colleagues of just how serious our debt crisis is. My goal is for each of them, every time they vote, to consider this rapidly growing number and how it will‚Äîand already is‚Äîaffecting the future of this country, our children, and grandchildren.

Another priority of mine is to help the counties and communities in my district without growing government. The PRIME Act is a piece of legislation I‚Äôve introduced that would serve all Americans, but would greatly benefit agricultural areas, such as Lewis County. Currently, in order to sell individual cuts of locally raised meats to consumers, farmers and ranchers must first send their animals to one of a limited number of USDA-inspected slaughterhouses. The PRIME Act would give individual states freedom to permit intrastate distribution of custom-slaughtered meat such as beef, pork, or lamb to consumers, restaurants, hotels, boarding houses, and grocery stores. I am hopeful that provisions from the PRIME Act will be included in this year‚Äôs Farm Bill. The PRIME Act would also be a fitting addition to Health Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr.‚Äôs plan to Make America Healthy Again (MAHA).

A special thank you to Joni Pugh, who serves on the Lewis County Chamber of Commerce Board of Directors, for inviting me to speak. I thoroughly enjoyed the meal and the opportunity to reconnect with so many people doing great things in Lewis County.

text:
üìö‚úèÔ∏è As Pennsylvania families prepare for Back to School, we know our teachers are once again stepping up‚Äîoften reaching into their own pockets to provide supplies for their students. 

In the current tax year, teachers cannot deduct more than $300 for school supplies. 

Under the recently passed OBBB, we‚Äôve made a commonsense change:

Starting in January 2026, teachers can deduct 100% of their unreimbursed classroom expenses.

So if a teacher spends $2,000 on classroom supplies, they can deduct the entire $2,000.

This is a big win for our educators, who should never be penalized for going the extra mile for their students.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Our nation lost a hero this week. Sgt. Michael Verardo‚Äôs life was the story of service, sacrifice, and love of country.

At just 40 years old, he was taken from us by the wounds he sustained in Afghanistan while serving with the 82nd Airborne. Gravely injured by an IED in 2010, Mike endured more than 120 surgeries and years of unimaginable pain‚Äîbut he refused to be broken. With his wife and high school sweetheart, Sarah, by his side, he turned sacrifice into service: lifting up his fellow warriors, leading in his community, and launching the Independence Fund‚Äôs Trackchair program, which restored freedom and dignity to thousands of America‚Äôs wounded veterans.

Mike‚Äôs story reminds us that the price of freedom is not abstract. It is written in the scars of our warriors and in the unshakable strength of their families. It is borne every day by those who serve and by those who love them.

Michael Verardo was a faithful servant. A patriot. A hero. As we mourn his passing, let us pray for his family‚Äîand let us honor his legacy by standing with every soldier, sailor, airman, Marine, and family who has borne the cost of liberty. The finest way to honor Sgt. Verardo and all who serve is to live as Americans worthy of their sacrifice‚Äîgrateful for liberty, united with one another, and committed to the cause of freedom.

Through daily affirmations, reflective journaling, and encouragement, she helps students see their worth and build the courage to try even when learning feels hard. Beyond the classroom, Ms. Brown mentors young girls in the Ladies of Distinction program, supports families at school events, and shows up for her community.

She was named the 2024‚Äì2025 Beginning Teacher of the Year at Gaston STEM Leadership Academy and Northampton County Schools. Ms. Brown is shaping the future one student at a time.

Mr. McInnish, a Coast Guard veteran, has dedicated 27 years to teaching technology and career education. He founded the first-ever aviation fabrication and assembly program at Eau Gallie HS, which led to it becoming the first school in the nation to award high school students with the National Aerospace/Aircraft Assembly certification.

text:
I was deeply saddened to learn of the untimely passing of Cleveland County Judge Jimmy Cummings. Judge Cummings was serving his first term as county judge, proving to be a dedicated leader and committed public servant who left an indelible mark on the Cleveland County community.

Judge Cummings was not only an exceptional public official but also a proud veteran who answered the call to serve his country with honor. His exemplary military service underscores his committed service to others, whether on the battlefield or in the halls of local government. Through his leadership, Judge Cummings embodied the values of integrity, courage, and selflessness.

Our prayers are with his family, friends, and all who had the privilege of knowing him. Cleveland County has lost a steadfast leader whose legacy of service remains an example to all. May God bless and comfort his loved ones during this difficult time.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share stories from across our district of neighbors whose courage, character, and quiet acts of service remind us what makes Bucks County such a special place to call home. Today, we honor a woman whose ordinary workday became an extraordinary act of heroism. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero, Sarah Van de Laar of Bensalem.
 
Sarah has spent the past six years serving our community as a @USPS letter carrier. Like so many of her colleagues, she is a familiar, steady presence in the lives of those along her route‚Äîsomeone neighbors count on day in and day out.
 
But one afternoon on Knights Road, Sarah‚Äôs route became anything but routine. She saw a car veer off the curb and crash, and in that moment, she didn‚Äôt think twice. She stopped, ran to the scene, and found the driver slumped over in his seat. She immediately called 911, pulled him from the vehicle with the help of a passerby, and began CPR. Calm, steady, and determined, she kept going until first responders arrived. Only later did she learn that her quick action had saved his life. And weeks later, when she saw him again face to face, she described that moment simply as ‚Äúa gift.‚Äù
 
In her own words, Sarah doesn‚Äôt see herself as a hero: ‚ÄúI just consider myself a human being. I come into my job every day, go home, and see my family.‚Äù That‚Äôs who she is‚Äîhumble, steady, devoted to her work and her community.  She reminds us that true heroism often comes from ordinary people who act with extraordinary courage when it matters most.
 
Our letter carriers don‚Äôt just deliver mail‚Äîthey deliver trust, connection, and care. They are often the first to notice when something is wrong, the ones who look out for our seniors, and the steady presence that keeps our communities connected day after day. Yet too often, their service is taken for granted. That is why I have made it a top priority to partner with our local carriers and advocates across the nation to ensure their voices are heard. Together, we‚Äôve fought to strengthen the Postal Service, secure fair treatment, and deliver the resources they need to keep doing their jobs with pride. Sarah‚Äôs courage is a reminder of the extraordinary humanity at the heart of this work‚Äîand why I will always stand shoulder to shoulder with our postal workers, here at home and across America.
 
Join me in celebrating Sarah for her bravery and service, and thanking every postal worker for the countless ways they keep our neighborhoods strong and our country moving forward. National Association of Letter Carriers

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: Happy birthday to John Locke, born this day in 1632. If you care about liberty, you should care about Locke. He gave us the intellectual backbone of America‚Äôs founding. üßµ https://t.co/6ys1RIjpT4

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: Locke believed every person is born with natural rights: life, liberty, and property. These rights, according to Locke, are given by God, not government. The government‚Äôs job is to protect them.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: And if government tramples those rights, the people have the right to resist. Radical in 17th-century England. Still radical in some corners of the world today. But accepted as truth in a nation as free as ours.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Why didn‚Äôt Founders use his exact words? Life, Liberty, and Property?

Because at the time, slaves in America were considered ‚Äúproperty.‚Äù Even though the Founders owned slaves, they were fundamentally abolitionists. They changed ‚Äúproperty‚Äù to ‚Äúpursuit of happiness‚Äù so that their words could never be used to justify slavery. The abolitionist movement referenced this fact constantly in the fight against slavery.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: The Founders read Locke closely. Jefferson‚Äôs Declaration, Madison‚Äôs defense of checks and balances, Hamilton‚Äôs distrust of concentrated power ‚Äî all echo Locke‚Äôs vision.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: Locke also rejected the idea that rulers govern by divine right. He argued rulers govern only by the consent of the governed. That principle, revolutionary for its day, sits at the core of our republic.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: So when you read the Declaration or the Constitution, remember Locke‚Äôs fingerprints are all over it. Our Founders built America on his conviction that liberty is God-given, and government exists to protect it.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
WOW you‚Äôre gonna want to watch this town hall. Though honestly the video doesn‚Äôt do it justice because it‚Äôs hard to hear how loud the protestors were.

I love the Kingwood community and townhalls here have ALWAYS been productive and educational, even when we might disagree. 

I always give updates on my work in Congress‚Äìespecially on flood mitigation since that affects Kingwood so profoundly. I always do Q&A. Always respectful.

Last night was different. 

Of the 400 people in the room, about fifty leftists would not stop interrupting with shouting and incoherent chanting. They demanded that we raise everyone's taxes, give free paychecks to able-bodied adults, and sneered at the success of the flood mitigation projects we‚Äôve done that have saved lives and property. 

First clue that most of these protesters probably weren't actual constituents: they tried to shout me down when I gave an update on funding for FLOOD MITIGATION, which is priority #1 in Kingwood. 

They‚Äôd know how important these projects are if they actually lived in Kingwood during Hurricane Harvey. 

Anyways, the protestors did a great job of annoying all the actual constituents in the room and made it really easy to identify themselves with their red cards (you‚Äôll see what I mean in the video. It was kind of hilarious actually). 

If the left keeps this up 2026 is going to be a really good year for Republicans. 

The left‚Äôs message is clear: raise your taxes, open the border back up, and encourage children to transition their gender. No thanks.

Name: Salinas, Andrea
text:
On Wednesday, U.S. Border Patrol arrested two firefighters who were working to combat the ongoing blaze in Washington‚Äôs Olympic Peninsula. At least one of those firefighters is a constituent from Keizer, OR. During his detention, my constituent was denied his constitutional right to an attorney and a phone call.

I‚Äôm appalled that the Trump Administration is arresting firefighters to meet their arbitrary deportation quotas. These firefighters risk their lives to keep us safe, and this is how Trump treats them. It‚Äôs sick and twisted. This does not make us safer or stronger. Border Patrol should not be prowling our national forests to arrest firefighters.

While I cannot provide the name of the firefighter, I can share additional details about his background and his unconstitutional detention. My constituent was brought to the United States when he was a young child and has lived here his entire life. The United States is the only home he knows. For the past three years, he has bravely served as a wildland firefighter, putting his life on the line to protect our communities.

Additionally, seven years ago, my constituent and his family were victims of a federal crime. As a result of cooperating with federal officials during their investigation, my constituent and his family became eligible for a ‚ÄúU visa.‚Äù Their application has been pending with USCIS for the past seven years and if granted would provide them legal status and a pathway to citizenship.

On August 27, my constituent was working to combat the Bear Gulch Wildfire when CBP stopped his crew and arrested him. Over the next nearly 48 hours, the whereabouts of my constituent were unknown. He was not entered into the ICE detainee locator.

I have since learned that my constituent was taken to the CBP facility in Bellingham Washington. His legal team called the CBP Bellingham station. The CBP attendant refused to confirm his detention location or grant them access. When they called again, the CBP attendant confirmed that he was being transferred to ICE custody but would not grant his attorney access.

On Friday, my constituent was moved to the Northwest ICE Processing Center in Tacoma, WA, where he was finally granted access to a phone call and called his attorneys, which is how we were able to learn his story.

As of now, he is still not in the ICE detainee locator.

I have also been in touch with my constituent‚Äôs lawyers. I‚Äôm deeply concerned that CBP has been concealing his whereabouts and has denied him due process. I‚Äôm working with my Congressional colleagues to hold the Trump Administration accountable and demand that they immediately provide details about the arrest and failure to honor my constituent‚Äôs rights.

Immigrants deserve to be treated with dignity. Communities deserve safety from wildfires, and first responders deserve protections from federal immigration officials while they are putting their lives on the line to protect our Pacific Northwest communities.

Name: Bean, Aaron
text:
üìçRoller Die + Forming in Green Cove Springs

For nearly 9 decades, Roller Die + Forming has been a leading producer of standard and custom roll formed parts all over the world. In roll forming, sheet metal passes through a specific set of matched rolls. Each set of rolls touches the passing metal and changes the shape resulting in the desired cross section.

The Green Cove Springs facility produces many different parts for various industries including heavy truck, bus, medical, and building products. 

With locations across the United States, Roller Die made the decision to relocate their headquarters to Florida as our state has the most business friendly climate bar none. 

During the tour, we discussed the jobs their facility brought to the region, the successes they are seeing via tariffs, and how the One, Big Beautiful Bill boosts American manufacturing. 

Included in the One, Big Beautiful Bill: 

‚úÖ Full expensing for new factories and factory improvements to accelerate domestic manufacturing.
‚úÖ Full expensing for domestic R&D to encourage domestic innovation.
‚úÖ Full expensing for new capital investments, like machinery and equipment, to boost domestic production.

I enjoyed spending time with the @Rollerdie team and learning more about their operations! #BeanOnTour #MadeInAmerica #Manufacturing

text:
This week, I had the opportunity to meet with local leaders, hardworking business owners, farmers, ranchers, and neighbors in Atascosa County who are working every day to strengthen our community. At the Atascosa County Courthouse and the Justice Center, I sat down with county officials to discuss how federal investments can advance local priorities and how I can keep delivering results in Washington.

In Pleasanton, I visited the Atascosa Health Center to talk about the challenges rural health centers face and the vital role they play in caring for families. Since FY24, I‚Äôve secured nearly $7 million through the HRSA Health Center Program for the Atascosa Health Center to expand services at their clinics and another $500,000 for the Atascosa County EMS Center. I‚Äôll keep working to ensure families in #TX28 have access to affordable, quality health care.

Later, I toured a local ranch to hear from the owners about ways I can strengthen agriculture and help lower costs for working families. Ranches and farms like these are a pillar of our communities and the heart of so many families.

I‚Äôll continue working with the hardworking families and county officials of Atascosa to identify new opportunities, cut through red tape, and make sure our communities have the tools they need to succeed.

The conservative philosopher and writer, Russell Kirk, wrote, ‚ÄúEvery right is married to a duty; every freedom owes a corresponding responsibility; and there cannot be genuine freedom unless there exists also genuine order, in the moral realm and in the social realm.‚Äù 

The American spirit has always understood this truth‚Äîa commitment to duty, community, and the sacrifices necessary to secure liberty. That is a recipe for heroism. 

American heroism does not only belong to those in uniform, but also to parents, neighbors, and workers who quietly shoulder their duties every day. 

Freedom is safeguarded when responsibility is embraced‚Äîwhen we honor one another, keep our word, and put service before self. In big ways and small, we preserve liberty by living with purpose, duty, and care for each other. That‚Äôs part of the fabric of American heroism and what makes our country great.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1985, the wreck of the Titanic was found 73 years after it sank.

Found about 400 miles east of Newfoundland and nearly 13,000 feet deep, the ship had broken in two but remained remarkably preserved, surrounded by a wide debris field.

Using a Navy-developed submersible called Argo, the team captured the first images of the ship, beginning with one of its boilers. The discovery revolutionized deep-sea exploration and renewed interest in the Titanic, leading to numerous expeditions, artifact recoveries, and greater understanding of its 1912 sinking.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Labor Day: recognizing the grit, resilience, and unmatched productivity of the American worker.

President Reagan spoke about our free labor system (and owning the rewards of your own labor), drawing a sharp contrast from the oppressive labor systems behind the Iron Curtain, where your labor belonged only to the communist elites. 

Those systems treated workers as tools of the state. Ours treat workers as individuals, free to earn, build, innovate, and thrive. It‚Äôs the reason America became the most prosperous nation in history while socialist regimes collapse.

The old famous Soviet line come to mind: ‚ÄúWe will pretend to work as long as they keep pretending to pay us!‚Äù That‚Äôs not a recipe for productivity or innovation. Achievements happen because people are incentivized by the belief that their hard work will pay off AND they‚Äôll own it, not the state. 

The people who produce very little resent this system, always voting for politicians who promise to take from the productive members of society and redistribute their wealth to them. They offer up some rationale of an unequal playing field, social justice, etc- whatever buzzword of the day fits their agenda. But in the end, succeeding in America is easier than in any other place in human history- combine talent, hard work, and stay out of jail. Happy Labor Day.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 31 B.C., Octavian defeated Mark Antony and Cleopatra in the Battle of Actium, which marked the end of the Roman Republic and the beginning of the Roman Empire.

Following the assassination of Julius Caesar, Octavian and Antony vied for control, culminating in the Battle of Actium.

Antony and his lover, Cleopatra, had a larger fleet, but Octavian and his ally, Agrippa, had superior strategic positioning. Cleopatra‚Äôs ship withdrew from the battle early on, and Antony followed her, abandoning his forces. This loss of morale led to a swift victory for Octavian and Agrippa.

Months later, Antony and Cleopatra committed suicide. Octavian, who would become Augustus, the first and most successful Roman emperor, reigned until his death in 14 A.D.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
üö®Last week, I again went to what will be the largest immigration detention center in the country, Camp East Montana. This is a $1.24 billion facility funded by Trump's "one big beautiful bill" located on Fort Bliss property.

I spoke to detainees and here are my takeaways üßµ

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
I first visited the day after it was declared to be "fully operational." 

IMO, it wasn't ready then, and it wasn't ready 10 days later when my team and I went back. 

One of the biggest issues for me: not enough federal personnel for strong oversight.
https://t.co/2gH0oWBzIk

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
My team and I spoke to dozens of detainees (about 1,400 men were detained on 8/28). 

Only one detainee had been in the U.S. for about a year; most of those I spoke to had been living and working in the U.S. for decades - one elderly man had lived in the U.S. for 37 years.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text: Among the men I spoke to: a long-haul driver who worked in the U.S. for 31 years; a small business owner who owned a salon and lived in Miami for 27 years; a man who worked in construction and others. Most have U.S. citizen wives and kids, pay taxes and were part of our economy.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
He'd never been arrested, wasn't speeding or breaking the law (he was racially profiled). 

His U.S. citizen wife tried to get his truck, phone and the cash back, but she was told that if her husband wanted those items back, he'd have to go pick them up (he was in ICE custody).

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
Some men had work permits that were canceled, or were in legal proceedings to adjust their status when they were apprehended. 

Many of the men we spoke to had come from "Alligator Alcatraz" which was shut down by a federal judge, and described terrible conditions there.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
One man was pulled over in Florida while on his way to buy construction supplies.

Local law enforcement arrested him for driving without a license, confiscated his truck, cell phone, $1500 in cash that belonged to his construction site supervisor and he was turned over to ICE.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
Construction had just been completed for the family and legal visitation that had been unavailable for the first 11 days of being "operational."

Legal organizations couldn't meet in person with their clients for nearly two weeks and had difficulty connecting by phone.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
One man said he was in pain and in desperate need of surgery (saying he had urinated blood) but was only given OTC pain meds.

Another was promised meds for severe allergies and never got it.

All described being fed foul-smelling food and drinking water that made them sick.

Name: Escobar, Veronica
text:
And there were still not enough federal employees on site for appropriate oversight.

This $1.24 BILLION corporate-run facility should not only NOT exist, but in a rush to be "operational," it's clear that @DHSgov was willing to serve bad food, limit legal access and more.

Name: Stefanik, Elise M.
text:
Today, I sent a letter to the @SecretaryLCD calling for a federal investigation into actions by Governor Hochul and Commissioner Martuscello that potentially violated The Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993 (FMLA).

In retaliation for the strike earlier this year by employees of the Department of Corrections and Community Supervision (DOCCS), Governor Hochul and her administration violated the Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993 (FMLA). Specifically, the state directed employees on FMLA leave to be classified as absent without leave (AWOL), resulting in their termination.

In a copy of an email obtained by my office, the DOCCS Deputy Commissioner for Administrative Services instructed prison superintendents that "staff who are calling in FMLA should be ordered in just like everyone else. If they refuse the order to report for duty, they should be made AWOL." These actions resulted in the wrongful termination of DOCCS employees, in violation of federal regulations.

By classifying DOCCS employees on FMLA as AWOL, Governor Hochul and the DOCCS Commissioner caused families to lose access to health insurance, accrued overtime pay, sick leave, and unemployment benefits. As the COs challenge their loss of employment through the grievance process or appeal the denial of their unemployment benefits, they are being slow-rolled through the process with no communication from the New York State Office of Employee Relations or the Department of Labor. This is a clear-cut, coordinated abuse of power by Governor Hochul and Commissioner Martuscello, specifically their actions to deny employment and earned benefits to Correctional Officers and DOCCS employees.

This is just the latest in a long line of abuses of power and blatant attacks on law enforcement by Governor Hochul and her administration. I request that you review the illegal actions taken by New York State and compel compliance with FMLA for those employees who were terminated while on approved leave.

READ MORE ‚¨áÔ∏è https://t.co/fiKvuMuTMZ
